This paper deals with the complexity of evaluating conjunctive queries over databases, which is a fundamental problem in database theory and falls under the category of database systems (cs.DB). The paper also introduces a notion of query acyclicity and studies its complexity, which is related to the area of logic in computer science (cs.LO). The paper uses techniques from computational complexity theory to analyze the complexity of various query problems, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also considers examples such as acyclic subgraph problems and multidimensional matching, which are related to the areas of algorithms and artificial intelligence (cs.DS and cs.AI). Overall, the paper covers a broad range of topics in computer science, but the focus on database systems and computational complexity suggests that cs.DB and cs.CC are the most likely categories.
